#### GPU Technology Conference (GTC)

Nvidia's annual GPU Technology Conference (GTC) has evolved from its origins in 2009 as a technical conference focused on GPU computing to a premier global event for artificial intelligence and [deep learning](/Deep_learning). GTC now explores applications in areas such as [self-driving cars](/Autonomous_car), healthcare, and [high-performance computing](/High_Performance_Computing), alongside training through the Nvidia Deep Learning Institute (DLI). GTC 2018 attracted over 8,400 attendees, while GTC 2020 transitioned to a digital format, drawing approximately 59,000 registrants. After several years of virtual events, GTC returned to an in-person format in San Jose, California, in March 2024. At GTC 2025, Nvidia unveiled its next-generation AI hardware, the Blackwell Ultra and Vera Rubin chips, signaling advancements toward [agentic AI](/Agentic_AI) and [reasoning-capable computing](/Reasoning_AI). Huang projected that AI-driven infrastructure would drive Nvidia's data center revenue to $1 trillion by 2028. The conference also introduced Isaac GR00T N1 (humanoid robotics model), Cosmos (a [synthetic training data](/Synthetic_training_data) AI), and the Newton physics engine, developed in collaboration with DeepMind and Disney Research.

#### Product Families

Nvidia's extensive product portfolio encompasses a wide range of hardware and software solutions:

*   [GeForce](/GeForce): Consumer-oriented graphics processing products.
*   [RTX](/Nvidia_RTX): Professional visual computing graphics processing products, succeeding the GTX and [Quadro](/Quadro) brands.
*   [NVS](/Nvidia_Quadro): Business graphics processors designed for multi-display applications.
*   [Tegra](/Tegra): A line of [system on a chip](/System_on_a_chip) (SoC) processors for mobile devices.
*   [Tesla](/Nvidia_Tesla): Dedicated general-purpose GPUs for high-end image generation in professional and scientific fields.
*   [nForce](/NForce): Motherboard chipsets for Intel and AMD microprocessors.
*   [GRID](/Nvidia_GRID): Hardware and services for graphics virtualization.
*   Shield: A range of gaming hardware, including the [Shield Portable](/Shield_Portable), [Shield Tablet](/Shield_Tablet), and [Shield TV](/Shield_TV).
*   [Drive](/Nvidia_Drive): Hardware and software solutions for autonomous vehicle development, including the [Drive PX-series](/Drive_PX-series) AI platform and the Driveworks operating system.
*   [BlueField](/Nvidia_BlueField): A line of [data processing units](/Data_processing_unit) (DPUs), inherited from the acquisition of [Mellanox Technologies](/Mellanox_Technologies).
*   Grace: A datacenter/server class CPU released in 2023.
*   [DGX](/Nvidia_DGX): An enterprise platform specifically designed for deep learning applications.
*   Maxine: A platform providing developers with a suite of AI-based conferencing software.
*   Omniverse: A platform for the creation and operation of [metaverse](/Metaverse) applications.

#### Open-Source Software Support

Historically, Nvidia's approach to open-source software support was a point of contention within the developer community. Until September 23, 2013, the company did not publish comprehensive documentation for its advanced hardware, necessitating [reverse engineering](/Reverse_engineering) for the development of [free and open-source](/Free_and_open-source) [device drivers](/Device_driver). While Nvidia provided proprietary binary drivers for [X.Org](/X.Org_Server) and an open-source library for kernel interfacing, its stance drew criticism from figures like [Linus Torvalds](/Linus_Torvalds). Many in the Linux and BSD communities advocated for greater transparency and support for open-source development, contrasting Nvidia's approach with that of competitors like [Intel](/Intel) and [AMD](/Advanced_Micro_Devices).

Nvidia's proprietary drivers were primarily available for x86/x64 and ARMv7-A architectures, limiting features like [CUDA](/CUDA) on other platforms. Accusations of artificial restrictions, such as limiting monitor usage, were not officially commented upon by the company. In 2014, with its Maxwell GPUs, Nvidia began requiring proprietary firmware to unlock full functionality.

A significant shift occurred on May 11, 2022, when Nvidia announced it was open-sourcing its GPU kernel modules. Support for Nvidia's firmware was subsequently integrated into the nouveau driver in 2023, enabling proper power management and GPU reclocking for newer graphics card generations. In July 2025, Nvidia announced an extension of CUDA support to RISC-V, further broadening its ecosystem.

Nvidia's open-source projects include:

*   [Nouveau](/Nouveau_(software))
